## §3 The 4+N Engine Architecture

### §3.1 Four Core Engines

The four Universal Dimensions require four core engines. Every commons needs all four. They are non-negotiable — they ship with every Commons OS fork.

| Engine | Dimension | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| **Purpose Engine** | D1 — Definition & Purpose | Direction, umbrella, governance of the entire commons |
| **Participation Engine** | D2 — Participation & Relationship | Community of practice of ALL stakeholders — human, AI, ecological |
| **Proposition Engine** | D3 — Proposition & Exchange | What we offer to produce to reach our purpose |
| **Production Engine** | D4 — Production & Resilience | The means to fulfil the proposed promise resiliently |

These names are universal. A forest ecosystem has a Purpose Engine (what the forest is, its boundary, its governance). A city has a Participation Engine (all inhabitants, visitors, institutions, species). A bakery has a Proposition Engine (bread, community gathering, seed dispersal of food culture). The names carry across all four commons domains without translation.

If the four engines collapse further (4 → 1), the result is the commons itself. The singularity IS Orbit 0. The four engines are four expressions of one living system, just as the four dimensions are four lenses on one reality. At the centre, they are one.

### §3.2 N Extension Engines

Extension engines are domain-specific. The number is unbounded — determined by D1 (the fork's purpose):

| Fork | Extension engine examples |
|---|---|
| Commons.Engineering | OS Engine (instance lifecycle, fork management, MCP orchestration) |
| Public transport operator | Fleet Engine, Network Engine, Passenger Engine |
| Safety technology company | Safety Engine, Regulatory Engine |
| City commons | Urban Planning Engine, Mobility Engine |
| Forest ecosystem | Biodiversity Engine, Hydrology Engine |

### §3.3 CE's Engine Implementations

Commons.Engineering implements the four core engines with names specific to its purpose:

| Universal engine | CE implementation | What CE calls it |
|---|---|---|
| Purpose Engine | Commons Engine | Produces and guards commons instances (D1) |
| Participation Engine | Community Engine | Content, learning, relationships, collaboration (D2) |
| Proposition Engine | Lighthouse Engine | Briefings, account management, proof of model (D3) |
| Production Engine | Context Engine | On-the-spot knowledge for visitors, engineers, lighthouses (D4) |

Other commons may name their implementations differently. But the four dimensions — and therefore the four core engines — are universal.

### §3.4 The OS Engine: CE's First Extension

The **OS Engine** is Commons.Engineering's first extension engine. It manages OS instance lifecycle:

- **Fork:** Create OS instances from the Commons OS template, wire MCP connections to CE intelligence services
- **Connect:** Discover sibling instances, manage the network graph
- **Lifecycle:** Manage instance states through the materialisation sequence (§10.1)
- **Aggregate:** Collect anonymised intelligence from instances back into the commons
- **Serve:** Provide instance-specific MCP endpoints at tiered access

The OS Engine is to commons instances what the Lighthouse Engine (CE's Proposition Engine) is to lighthouses.

### §3.5 Value Stream Families

Beneath the four engines, **value stream families** boot once D1 (Purpose) is in place. These are domain-specific collections of patterns that customise the commons for its territory:

- Urban commons loads urban value stream families (housing, transport, energy, food, governance…)
- Business commons loads business value stream families (supply chain, innovation, stewardship, talent…)
- Life commons loads life value stream families (nutrition, cognition, community, movement…)
- Ecology commons loads ecology value stream families (biodiversity, hydrology, carbon, soil…)

Value stream families are **Curated Pattern Collections** — produced by the Proposition Engine (D3). They are not engines. They are the content that the engines process.

The T-shaped practitioner model applies: deep expertise in one value stream family, broad shoulders across others, coordinated by "Senior Ts" responsible for an entire dimension.

