### §8.2 Platform Infrastructure

The repository is the body. The platform infrastructure is the nervous system. Both come with the fork.

| Infrastructure | Pre-configured in the template | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Issue tracker** | Issue templates for deliberation, decision, build, spec | Every idea → an issue. Every decision → a labelled issue. The closing commit IS the decision record. |
| **Project board** | Columns matching the materialisation sequence (§10.1) | Visual state of all commons work. Humans and agents read the same board. |
| **Labels** | By dimension (`definition`, `participation`, `proposition`, `production`), by type (`deliberation`, `decision`, `build`), by priority | Machine-readable intent. An agent can query, prioritise, and propose. A human can scan and decide. |
| **Milestones** | Aligned with the Living Blueprint phases | Connect daily work to the boot sequence and longer-term outcomes. |
| **Branch protection** | Main branch protected, PR-based workflow | The secure environment. Experimentation on branches, validated changes to main. |
| **Git hooks / CI** | Spec conformance checks, pattern validation | Automated quality — the OS validates its own integrity on every commit. |

This is what makes Organisation as Code concrete. The issue tracker is the governance runtime. The board is the operations dashboard. The labels are the shared vocabulary between humans and agents. Git is the institutional memory. Together, they make the commons a self-documenting, self-governing, self-improving organisation from the moment of fork.

### §8.3 What the AGENT.md Contains

The AGENT.md (or equivalent for other cognitive infrastructure) is the configuration that connects the commons to the OS:

- **Commons MCP endpoints** — connections to the four core engines, the three collections, and the onboarding flow
- **Organisation MCP endpoints** — connections to the commons' own proprietary systems (CRM, ERP, knowledge bases, etc.)
- **Extension engine endpoints** — connections to domain-specific engines relevant to this commons' purpose
- **Onboarding guidance** — step-by-step instructions for the Living Blueprint boot sequence
- **Pattern language context** — which patterns, which taxonomy, which orbital layers are relevant to this commons' purpose
- **Participation tier** — what level of access this commons has to the intelligence layer

The AGENT.md is what makes "fork → boot → operate" possible. Without it, the workspace is an empty skeleton. With it, the agent can guide a new commons through its entire startup sequence.

Each OS instance gets its own agent with deep knowledge of its domain (the T's vertical) and broad awareness across all four dimensions (the T's horizontal). The agent is a participant — it has perspective.

### §8.4 Private Workshop, Intranet, Extranet

Every commons follows the same publishing path:

| Layer | What | Visibility | Technology (examples) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Workshop** | Where the real work happens | Private | GitHub private repo |
| **Intranet** | Commons community's internal site | Community-only | GitHub Pages + Hugo |
| **Extranet** | Public-facing presence | Public | Cloudflare Pages |

The workshop is private and stays private. Selective publishing to intranet and extranet follows a git-based workflow.

