## §9 Linking Model

### §9.1 Flat Links, Not Hierarchy

Every link is a direct reference by slug. There are no intermediate layers unless connections demand them.

**Start flat. Add layers only when connections confuse. Always consider building them back.**

### §9.2 The ≥3 Nodes Rule

From the cloudsters Organisational Architecture: new governance layers form only when three or more active nodes below need coordination. This prevents premature hierarchy creation.

### §9.3 When to Add and Remove Layers

Add an intermediate grouping (e.g., "Baltic-Hanse", "DACH") **only when**:
1. More than ~20 commons link at the same level and navigation becomes confusing
2. There is operational activity at the intermediate level (a coordinator, a shared programme)
3. The grouping has cultural or economic coherence

Remove a layer when:
1. It has no active participation
2. Its commons can link directly to the next level without confusion
3. It was created speculatively rather than from operational need

The default state is flat. Structure is earned, not assumed.

### §9.4 Lighthouse References

A lighthouse's `commons` field references the commons instance(s) that produced it. In the set-theory model, a lighthouse may be visible through multiple commons lenses. In the multiplicity model, the same entity may have distinct lighthouse instances produced by different commons.

Continental groupings may emerge when density justifies them. They are not pre-built.

